## Installation and Setup

### Step 1: Clone or Download Project
```bash
# If using Git
git clone <repository-url>
cd helloworldwithapi-lamda-tf

# Or download and extract the ZIP file
unzip helloworldwithapi-lamda-tf.zip
cd helloworldwithapi-lamda-tf
```

### Step 2: Configure AWS Credentials

#### Option A: AWS CLI Configuration
```bash
aws configure
# Enter your AWS Access Key ID
# Enter your AWS Secret Access Key
# Enter your default region (us-east-1)
# Enter default output format (json)
```

#### Option B: Environment Variables
```bash
export AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID=your_access_key
export AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=your_secret_key
export AWS_DEFAULT_REGION=us-east-1
```

### Step 3: Verify AWS Configuration
```bash
# Test AWS CLI configuration
aws sts get-caller-identity

# Test permissions
aws iam get-user
```

### Step 4: Install Terraform (if not already installed)
```bash
# Download Terraform
wget https://releases.hashicorp.com/terraform/1.5.0/terraform_1.5.0_linux_amd64.zip
unzip terraform_1.5.0_linux_amd64.zip
sudo mv terraform /usr/local/bin/

# Verify installation
terraform version
```

---

## Deployment Guide

### Method 1: Automated Deployment (Recommended)

#### Using Deploy Script
```bash
# Make script executable
chmod +x deploy.sh

# Run deployment
./deploy.sh
```

#### Using Make Commands
```bash
# Initialize Terraform
make init

# Plan deployment
make plan

# Apply configuration
make apply
```

### Method 2: Manual Deployment

#### Step 1: Package Lambda Function
```bash
zip -j lambda_function.zip index.py
```

#### Step 2: Initialize Terraform
```bash
terraform init
```

#### Step 3: Validate Configuration
```bash
terraform validate
```

#### Step 4: Plan Deployment
```bash
terraform plan -out=tfplan
```

#### Step 5: Apply Configuration
```bash
terraform apply tfplan
```

#### Step 6: Verify Deployment
```bash
terraform output
```

### Deployment Verification

After successful deployment, you should see:
```
api_endpoint = "https://abc123xyz.execute-api.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/"
lambda_function_name = "hello-world-function"
api_id = "abc123xyz"
```

---

## Testing Procedures

### Automated Testing

#### Using Make Command
```bash
make test
```

#### Using Curl
```bash
# Get API endpoint
API_ENDPOINT=$(terraform output -raw api_endpoint)

# Test the API
curl -s "$API_ENDPOINT" | jq .
```

### Manual Testing

#### Browser Testing
1. Open web browser
2. Navigate to the API endpoint URL
3. Verify JSON response is displayed

#### Command Line Testing
```bash
# Basic test
curl https://your-api-endpoint.amazonaws.com/

# With headers
curl -H "Accept: application/json" https://your-api-endpoint.amazonaws.com/

# Verbose output
curl -v https://your-api-endpoint.amazonaws.com/
```

### Expected Test Results

#### Success Response (200 OK)
```json
{
  "message": "Hello, World! Anand",
  "description": "This is a simple API powered by AWS Lambda and API Gateway",
  "request_id": "12345678-1234-1234-1234-123456789012"
}
```

#### Response Headers
```
content-type: application/json
access-control-allow-origin: *
content-length: 123
date: Mon, 13 Apr 2026 10:30:00 GMT
```

### Load Testing

#### Basic Load Test
```bash
# Simple load test with 10 concurrent requests
for i in {1..10}; do
  curl -s "$API_ENDPOINT" &
done
wait
```

#### Advanced Load Testing (using Apache Bench)
```bash
# Install Apache Bench
sudo apt-get install apache2-utils

# Run load test
ab -n 100 -c 10 "$API_ENDPOINT"
```

